\section{Few-shot classification with large language models}

In-context learning is the idea to use large language models to complete tasks in a few-shot or zero-shot way. In this assignment, we will classify Swedish political manifesto quotes as belonging to either the Social Democratic party (\texttt{Socialdemokraterna}) or the Conservative party (\texttt{Moderaterna}).

The goal is not only to get answers from a chatbot, but to use an LLM as a classifier through an API from R, store the outputs in a structured format, and evaluate the classifier properly.

\subsection{OpenAI API setup from R}

For this assignment, you need an OpenAI developer account and an API key. A ChatGPT Plus subscription is not the same thing as API access, so make sure you create the key in the developer platform.

\textcolor{red}{\emph{Warning:}} Never write your API key directly in your script, report, or any file that may be uploaded to a public repository. Store it as an environment variable instead.

We will use the \texttt{ellmer} R package, which provides a modern R interface to LLM APIs and supports structured outputs.

<<eval=FALSE>>=
install.packages("ellmer")
@

Store your key in \texttt{.Renviron}. The easiest way is to run:

<<eval=FALSE>>=
install.packages("usethis")
usethis::edit_r_environ()
@

Add the following line to the file, replacing the placeholder with your actual key:

<<eval=FALSE>>=
OPENAI_API_KEY="[YOUR KEY GOES HERE]"
@

Save the file and restart R. You can then check that R can see the key:

<<eval=FALSE>>=
Sys.getenv("OPENAI_API_KEY") != ""
@

For this assignment, use \texttt{gpt-5.4-mini} for development and your main experiments. At the end, compare your final classifier with \texttt{gpt-5.5}. Use low temperature so the task is closer to classification than creative generation.

<<eval=FALSE>>=
library(ellmer)

system_message <- paste(
  "You are a careful research assistant classifying",
  "Swedish political manifesto quotes."
)

chat_mini <- chat_openai(
  model = "gpt-5.4-mini",
  system_prompt = system_message,
  params = params(temperature = 0),
  echo = "none"
)

chat_55 <- chat_openai(
  model = "gpt-5.5",
  system_prompt = system_message,
  params = params(temperature = 0),
  echo = "none"
)
@

\emph{Note!} API calls cost money. Start with a very small subset to check that your prompt, schema, and evaluation code work before running the model on more observations.

\subsection{Data}

\emph{Note!} This data is included in \texttt{uuml} version 0.4.0 and later.

<<eval=FALSE>>=
library(uuml)
data("pc_test")
data("pc_train")
@

Check how the party labels are stored. The model output will use \texttt{Socialdemokraterna} and \texttt{Moderaterna}, so create a comparable gold-standard label if the data uses abbreviations such as \texttt{S} and \texttt{M}.

<<eval=FALSE>>=
table(pc_train$party)
table(pc_test$party)
}

@

\subsection{Structured outputs}

Do not parse free text answers from the model. Instead, require a structured output with three fields: the predicted party, a confidence score, and a short reason.

\subsection{In-Context Learning for few-shot classification}

\subsection{Prompt construction}

Create a small, balanced set of examples from the training data and use them to build a few-shot classification prompt.

<<eval=TRUE>>=
library(uuml)
data("pc_test")
data("pc_train")
<<eval=FALSE>>=
    "Classify the Swedish political manifesto quote.",
    "Allowed labels: Socialdemokraterna or Moderaterna.",
    paste(
      "Use policy content, ideological cues, and style.",
      "Do not rely only on single words."
    )
@

\subsection{Small pilot run}

Before classifying the full test set, run the model on a small random subset of approximately 10 test quotes. Inspect the returned \texttt{party}, \texttt{confidence}, and \texttt{reason} fields. If the output looks wrong, revise your prompt before continuing.

<<eval=FALSE>>=
set.seed(123)
pilot_ids <- sample(seq_len(nrow(pc_test)), 10)
pc_pilot <- pc_test[pilot_ids, ]



pilot_predictions$party_pred <- as.character(pilot_predictions$party)
pilot_predictions$party <- NULL
pilot_results <- cbind(pc_pilot, pilot_predictions)
pilot_results[, c("quote", "party_gold", "party_pred", "confidence", "reason")]
@

\subsection{Evaluation}

After your pilot works, classify the test set or a clearly justified subset of the test set. Compute the confusion matrix, accuracy, balanced accuracy, precision, recall, and F1 score.


For example:

<<eval=FALSE>>=
)


mini_predictions$party_pred <- as.character(mini_predictions$party)
mini_predictions$party <- NULL
mini_results <- cbind(pc_test, mini_predictions)
mini_metrics <- classification_metrics(
  truth = mini_results$party_gold,
  estimate = mini_results$party_pred
)

mini_metrics
@

\subsection{Model comparison}

Use the same final prompt and the same evaluation cases to compare \texttt{gpt-5.4-mini} with \texttt{gpt-5.5}. If API costs are a concern, compare both models on a random subset of at least 30 test quotes and state clearly that you used a subset.

<<eval=FALSE>>=
comparison_ids <- sample(seq_len(nrow(pc_test)), 30)
pc_compare <- pc_test[comparison_ids, ]

@

Discuss whether \texttt{gpt-5.5} improves the classification enough to justify using the larger model for this task. Compare performance, confidence, errors, and practical issues such as latency and cost.

\subsection{What to hand in}

Your report should include:


\begin{enumerate}
\item A short description of your few-shot prompt and how you selected the demonstrations.
\item The structured output schema used for the model response.
\item Results from the small pilot run, including any prompt changes you made after inspecting it.
\item Proper evaluation of your final \texttt{gpt-5.4-mini} classifier: confusion matrix, accuracy, balanced accuracy, precision, recall, and F1.
\item A comparison between \texttt{gpt-5.4-mini} and \texttt{gpt-5.5} on the same evaluation cases.
\item A short discussion of what kinds of quotes the model misclassified and whether the larger model was worth using.
\end{enumerate}

